04094nam a22005535i 9780822393436DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20112011ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223934367 a10.1515/97808223934362doi  a(DE-B1597)553470  a(OCoLC)708741601  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHC440.I55bR334 2011 7aSOC0260002bisacsh04a305.5/5309542221 aRadhakrishnan, Smitha, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAppropriately Indian :bGender and Culture in a New Transnational Class /cSmitha Radhakrishnan. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2011] 4cÂ©2011  a1 online resource (252 p.) :b13 illustrations, 1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION: ON BACKGROUND -- t1. PRIVILEGE -- t2. GLOBAL/INDIAN -- t3. MERIT -- t4. INDIVIDUALS -- t5. FAMILY -- t6. RELIGION -- tCONCLUSION: APOLITICAL POLITICS -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAppropriately Indian is an ethnographic analysis of the class of information technology professionals at the symbolic helm of globalizing India. Comprising a small but prestigious segment of India's labor force, these transnational knowledge workers dominate the country's economic and cultural scene, as do their notions of what it means to be Indian. Drawing on the stories of Indian professionals in Mumbai, Bangalore, Silicon Valley, and South Africa, Smitha Radhakrishnan explains how these high-tech workers create a "global Indianness" by transforming the diversity of Indian cultural practices into a generic, mobile set of "Indian" norms. Female information technology professionals are particularly influential. By reconfiguring notions of respectable femininity and the "good" Indian family, they are reshaping ideas about what it means to be Indian.Radhakrishnan explains how this transnational class creates an Indian culture that is self-consciously distinct from Western culture, yet compatible with Western cosmopolitan lifestyles. She describes the material and symbolic privileges that accrue to India's high-tech workers, who often claim ordinary middle-class backgrounds, but are overwhelmingly urban and upper caste. They are also distinctly apolitical and individualistic. Members of this elite class practice a decontextualized version of Hinduism, and they absorb the ideas and values that circulate through both Indian and non-Indian multinational corporations. Ultimately, though, global Indianness is rooted and configured in the gendered sphere of home and family.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aGlobalizationxSocial aspectszIndia. 0aInformation technologyxEconomic aspectszIndia. 0aInformation technologyxSocial aspectszIndia. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822393436zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822393436423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822393436.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles